  67,1,Blessed is the One in Whose Hands rests all authority. And He is Most Capable of everything
  67,2,"ňĻHe is the Oneňļ Who created death and life in order to test which of you is best in deeds. And He is the Almighty, All-Forgiving"
  67,3,"ňĻHe is the Oneňļ Who created seven heavens, one above the other. You will never see any imperfection in the creation of the Most Compassionate.¬†So look again: do you see any flaws"
  67,4,Then look again and again‚ÄĒyour sight will return frustrated and weary
  67,5,"And indeed, We adorned the lowest heaven with ňĻstars likeňļ lamps, and made them ňĻas missilesňļ for stoning ňĻeavesdroppingňļ devils, for whom We have also prepared the torment of the Blaze"
  67,6,Those who disbelieve in their Lord will suffer the punishment of Hell. What an evil destination
  67,7,"When they are tossed into it, they will hear its roaring as it boils over"
  67,8,"almost bursting in fury. Every time a group is cast into it, its keepers will ask them, ‚ÄúDid a warner not come to you?‚ÄĚ"
  67,9,"They will reply, ‚ÄúYes, a warner did come to us, but we denied and said, ‚ÄėAllah has revealed nothing. You are extremely astray.‚Äô‚ÄĚ"
  67,10,"And they will lament, ‚ÄúIf only we had listened and reasoned, we would not be among the residents of the Blaze!‚ÄĚ"
  67,11,And so they will confess their sins. So away with the residents of the Blaze
  67,12,"Indeed, those in awe of their Lord without seeing Him¬†will have forgiveness and a mighty reward"
  67,13,Whether you speak secretly or openly‚ÄĒHe surely knows best what is ňĻhiddenňļ in the heart
  67,14,"How could He not know His Own creation? For He ňĻaloneňļ is the Most Subtle, All-Aware"
  67,15,"He is the One Who smoothed out the earth for you, so move about in its regions and eat from His provisions. And to Him is the resurrection ňĻof allňļ"
  67,16,Do you feel secure that the One Who is in heaven will not cause the earth to swallow you up as it quakes violently
  67,17,Or do you feel secure that the One Who is in heaven will not unleash upon you a storm of stones. Only then would you know how ňĻseriousňļ My warning was
  67,18,"And certainly those before them denied ňĻas wellňļ, then how severe was My response"
  67,19,"Have they not seen the birds above them, spreading and folding their wings? None holds them up except the Most Compassionate. Indeed, He is All-Seeing of everything"
  67,20,"Also, which ňĻpowerlessňļ force will come to your help instead of the Most Compassionate? Indeed, the disbelievers are only ňĻlostňļ in delusion"
  67,21,"Or who is it that will provide for you if He withholds His provision? In fact, they persist in arrogance and aversion ňĻto the truthňļ"
  67,22,"Who is ňĻrightlyňļ guided: the one who crawls facedown or the one who walks upright on the Straight Path"
  67,23,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúHe is the One Who brought you into being and gave you hearing, sight, and intellect. ňĻYetňļ you hardly give any thanks.‚ÄĚ"
  67,24,"ňĻAlsoňļ say, ‚ÄúHe is the One Who has dispersed you ňĻallňļ over the earth, and to Him you will ňĻallňļ be gathered.‚ÄĚ"
  67,25,"ňĻStillňļ they ask ňĻthe believersňļ, ‚ÄúWhen will this threat come to pass, if what you say is true?‚ÄĚ"
  67,26,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúThat knowledge is with Allah alone, and I am only sent with a clear warning.‚ÄĚ"
  67,27,"Then when they see the torment drawing near, the faces of the disbelievers will become gloomy, and it will be said ňĻto themňļ, ‚ÄúThis is what you claimed would never come.‚ÄĚ"
  67,28,"Say, ňĻO Prophet,ňļ ‚ÄúConsider this: whether Allah causes me and those with me to die or shows us mercy, who will save the disbelievers from a painful punishment?‚ÄĚ"
  67,29,"Say, ‚ÄúHe is the Most Compassionate‚ÄĒin Him ňĻaloneňļ we believe, and in Him ňĻaloneňļ we trust. You will soon know who is clearly astray.‚ÄĚ"
  67,30,"Say, ‚ÄúConsider this: if your water were to sink ňĻinto the earthňļ, then who ňĻelseňļ could bring you flowing water?‚ÄĚ"
  68,1,NŇ©n. By the pen and what everyone writes
  68,2,"By the grace of your Lord, you ňĻO Prophetňļ are not insane"
  68,3,You will certainly have a never-ending reward
  68,4,And you are truly ňĻa manňļ of outstanding character
  68,5,Soon you and the pagans will see
  68,6,which of you is mad
  68,7,Surely your Lord ňĻaloneňļ knows best who has strayed from His Way and who is ňĻrightlyňļ guided
  68,8,So do not give in to the deniers
  68,9,They wish you would compromise so they would yield ňĻto youňļ
  68,10,"And do not obey the despicable, vain oath-taker"
  68,11,"slanderer, gossip-monger"
  68,12,"withholder of good, transgressor, evildoer"
  68,13,"brute, and‚ÄĒon top of all that‚ÄĒan illegitimate child"
  68,14,"Now, ňĻsimplyňļ because he has been blessed with ňĻabundantňļ wealth and children"
  68,15,"whenever Our revelations are recited to him, he says, ‚ÄúAncient fables!‚ÄĚ"
  68,16,We will soon mark his snout
  68,17,"Indeed, We have tested those ňĻMeccansňļ as We tested the owners of the garden‚ÄĒwhen they swore they would surely harvest ňĻallňļ its fruit in the early morning"
  68,18,leaving no thought for Allah‚Äôs Will
  68,19,Then it was struck by a torment from your Lord while they slept
  68,20,so it was reduced to ashes
  68,21,Then by daybreak they called out to each other
  68,22,"ňĻsaying,ňļ ‚ÄúGo early to your harvest, if you want to pick ňĻallňļ the fruit.‚ÄĚ"
  68,23,"So they went off, whispering to one another"
  68,24,‚ÄúDo not let any poor person enter your garden today.‚ÄĚ
  68,25,"And they proceeded early, totally fixated on their purpose"
  68,26,"But when they saw it ňĻdevastatedňļ, they cried, ‚ÄúWe must have lost ňĻourňļ way"
  68,27,"In fact, we have been deprived ňĻof our livelihoodňļ.‚ÄĚ"
  68,28,"The most sensible of them said, ‚ÄúDid I not urge you to say, ‚ÄėAllah willing.‚Äô?‚ÄĚ"
  68,29,"They replied, ‚ÄúGlory be to our Lord! We have truly been wrongdoers.‚ÄĚ"
  68,30,"Then they turned on each other, throwing blame"
  68,31,"They said, ‚ÄúWoe to us! We have certainly been transgressors"
  68,32,"We trust our Lord will give us a better garden than this, ňĻforňļ we are indeed turning to our Lord with hope.‚ÄĚ"
  68,33,"That is the ňĻway of Ourňļ punishment ňĻin this worldňļ. But the punishment of the Hereafter is certainly far worse, if only they knew"
  68,34,"Indeed, the righteous will have the Gardens of Bliss with their Lord"
  68,35,Should We then treat those who have submitted like the wicked
  68,36,What is the matter with you? How do you judge
  68,37,"Or do you have a scripture, in which you read"
  68,38,that you will have whatever you choose
  68,39,Or do you have oaths binding on Us until the Day of Judgment that you will have whatever you decide
  68,40,Ask them ňĻO Prophetňļ which of them can guarantee all that
  68,41,"Or do they have associate-gods ňĻsupporting this claimňļ? Then let them bring forth their associate-gods, if what they say is true"
  68,42,"ňĻBeware ofňļ the Day the Shin ňĻof Allahňļ will be bared,¬†and the wicked will be asked to prostrate, but they will not be able to do so"
  68,43,"with eyes downcast, totally covered with disgrace. For they were ňĻalwaysňļ called to prostrate ňĻin the worldňļ when they were fully capable ňĻbut they chose not toňļ"
  68,44,So leave to Me ňĻO Prophetňļ those who reject this message. We will gradually draw them to destruction in ways they cannot comprehend
  68,45,"I ňĻonlyňļ delay their end for a while, but My planning is flawless"
  68,46,Or are you asking them for a reward ňĻfor the messageňļ so that they are overburdened by debt
  68,47,"Or do they have access to ňĻthe Record inňļ the unseen, so they copy it ňĻfor all to seeňļ"
  68,48,"So be patient with your Lord‚Äôs decree, and do not be like ňĻJonah,ňļ the Man of the Whale, who cried out ňĻto Allahňļ, in total distress"
  68,49,"Had he not been shown grace by his Lord, he would have certainly been cast onto the open ňĻshoreňļ, still blameworthy"
  68,50,"Then his Lord chose him, making him one of the righteous"
  68,51,"The disbelievers would almost cut you down with their eyes when they hear ňĻyou reciteňļ the Reminder,¬†and say, ‚ÄúHe is certainly a madman.‚ÄĚ"
  68,52,But it is simply a reminder to the whole world
  69,1,The Inevitable Hour
  69,2,What is the Inevitable Hour
  69,3,And what will make you realize what the Inevitable Hour is
  69,4,ňĻBothňļ Tham√Ľd and ‚Äô»ād denied the Striking Disaster
  69,5,"As for Tham√Ľd, they were destroyed by an overwhelming blast"
  69,6,"And as for ‚Äô»ād, they were destroyed by a furious, bitter wind"
  69,7,"which Allah unleashed on them non-stop for seven nights and eight days, so that you would have seen its people lying dead like trunks of uprooted palm trees"
  69,8,Do you see any of them left alive
  69,9,"Also, Pharaoh and those before him, and ňĻthe people ofňļ the overturned cities ňĻof Lotňļ indulged in sin"
  69,10,"each disobeying their Lord‚Äôs messenger, so He seized them with a crushing grip"
  69,11,"Indeed, when the floodwater had overflowed, We carried you¬†in the floating Ark ňĻwith Noahňļ"
  69,12,"so that We may make this a reminder to you, and that attentive ears may grasp it"
  69,13,"At last, when the Trumpet will be blown with one blast"
  69,14,and the earth and mountains will be lifted up and crushed with one blow
  69,15,on that Day the Inevitable Event will have come to pass
  69,16,The sky will then be so torn that it will be frail
  69,17,with the angels on its sides. On that Day eight ňĻmighty angelsňļ will bear the Throne of your Lord above them
  69,18,"You will then be presented ňĻbefore Him for judgmentňļ, and none of your secrets will stay hidden"
  69,19,"As for those given their records in their right hand, they will cry ňĻhappilyňļ, ‚ÄúHere ňĻeveryoneňļ! Read my record"
  69,20,I surely knew I would face my reckoning.‚ÄĚ
  69,21,They will be in a life of bliss
  69,22,in an elevated Garden
  69,23,whose fruit will hang within reach
  69,24,"ňĻThey will be told,ňļ ‚ÄúEat and drink joyfully for what you did in the days gone by.‚ÄĚ"
  69,25,"And as for those given their record in their left hand, they will cry ňĻbitterlyňļ, ‚ÄúI wish I had not been given my record"
  69,26,nor known anything of my reckoning
  69,27,I wish death was the end
  69,28,My wealth has not benefited me
  69,29,My authority has been stripped from me.‚ÄĚ
  69,30,"ňĻIt will be said,ňļ ‚ÄúSeize and shackle them"
  69,31,then burn them in Hell
  69,32,then tie them up with chains seventy arms long
  69,33,"For they never had faith in Allah, the Greatest"
  69,34,nor encouraged the feeding of the poor
  69,35,So this Day they will have no close friend here
  69,36,nor any food except ňĻoozingňļ pus
  69,37,which none will eat except the evildoers.‚ÄĚ
  69,38,"Now, I do swear by whatever you see"
  69,39,and whatever you cannot see
  69,40,"Indeed, this ňĻQuranňļ is the recitation of a noble Messenger"
  69,41,"It is not the prose of a poet ňĻas you claimňļ, ňĻyetňļ you hardly have any faith"
  69,42,"Nor is it the mumbling of a fortune-teller, ňĻyetňļ you are hardly mindful"
  69,43,ňĻIt isňļ a revelation from the Lord of all worlds
  69,44,Had the Messenger made up something in Our Name
  69,45,We would have certainly seized him by his right hand
  69,46,then severed his aorta
  69,47,and none of you could have shielded him ňĻfrom Usňļ
  69,48,"Indeed, this ňĻQuranňļ is a reminder to those mindful ňĻof Allahňļ"
  69,49,And We certainly know that some of you will persist in denial
  69,50,and it will surely be a source of regret for the disbelievers
  69,51,"And indeed, this ňĻQuranňļ is the absolute truth"
  69,52,"So glorify the Name of your Lord, the Greatest"
  70,1,A challenger¬†has demanded a punishment bound to come
  70,2,for the disbelievers‚ÄĒto be averted by none‚ÄĒ
  70,3,"from Allah, Lord of pathways of ňĻheavenlyňļ ascent"
  70,4,ňĻthrough whichňļ the angels and the ňĻholyňļ spirit¬†will ascend to Him on a Day fifty thousand years in length
  70,5,"So endure ňĻthis denial, O Prophet,ňļ with beautiful patience"
  70,6,They truly see this ňĻDayňļ as impossible
  70,7,but We see it as inevitable
  70,8,On that Day the sky will be like molten brass
  70,9,and the mountains like ňĻtufts ofňļ wool
  70,10,And no close friend will ask ňĻaboutňļ their friends
  70,11,ňĻalthoughňļ they will be made to see each other. The wicked will wish to ransom themselves from the punishment of that Day by their children
  70,12,"their spouses, their siblings"
